fr:mainmatter.html:p:
For examples:


The rule instance with the single premise-argument p \;/\; q and the conclusion-argument p \land  q \;/\; r is written as:


\usepackage {ebproof}
\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {p \;/\; q}
\infer 1[]{p \land  q \;/\; r}
\end {prooftree}



The rule instance with the two premise-arguments p \;/\; p and p \;/\; q and the conclusion-argument p, q \;/\; p is written as:


\usepackage {ebproof}
\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {p \;/\; p}
\hypo {p \;/\; q}
\infer 2[]{p, q \;/\; p}
\end {prooftree}



The rule instance with the empty set of premise-arguments and the conclusion-argument q \rightarrow  r \;/\; s is written as:


\usepackage {ebproof}
\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {}
\infer 1[]{q \rightarrow  r \;/\; s}
\end {prooftree}

fr:resource.fr:resource-source:
\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {p \;/\; q}
\infer 1[]{p, q, r, s, p \land  q, \neg  r \;/\; q}
\end {prooftree}

\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {p, q \;/\; r}
\hypo {p, q, r \;/\; s}
\infer 2[]{p, q \;/\; s}
\end {prooftree}

\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {p \land  q, r \lor  s \;/\; p \land  s}
\infer 1[]{\top  \land  (p \land  q), (t \rightarrow  s) \lor  s \;/\; \top  \land  s}
\end {prooftree}

fr:mainmatter.html:p:
It is not.
Here's a counterexample: a Boolean valuation v where:

v(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}

v(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}

v(s) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}

v(t) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}

We can think about these in turn:
if v(
eg A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, then since v is a strong Kleene valuation, it must be that v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}, so since A has the \mathsf {\mathbf {*}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {B}} property, we know t(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}, so since t is a Dunn-Belnap valuation t(
eg A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}};
if v(
eg A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}, then by similar reasoning v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, so t(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, so t(
eg A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}; and
if v(
eg A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}, then by similar reasoning v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}, so t(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}, so t(
eg A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}.

Let's look at each in turn:

if v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, then since v is a Dunn-Belnap valuation we know v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}. Since A has the property, this means s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}} too; and then since s is a strong Kleene valuation, we get s(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}};

by similar reasoning, if v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}, then v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}, so s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}, so s(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}};

by similar reasoning, if v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}, then v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}, so s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}, so s(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}; and

by similar reasoning, if v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}, then v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, so s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, so s(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}.

The key new ideas in this lecture are the idea of a matrix, and of the logic determined by a matrix.
We've seen four examples of this idea, and used them to name four particular logics:

designating \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} in the Boolean structure gives us a matrix that determines classical logic;

designating \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} in the strong Kleene structure gives us a matrix that determines the logic K3;

designating \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} and \mathsf {\mathbf {*}} in the strong Kleene structure gives us a matrix that determines the logic LP; and

designating \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} and \mathsf {\mathbf {B}} in the Dunn-Belnap structure gives us a matrix that determines the logic FDE.

Thinking this way brings at least two benefits: one practical and one conceptual. Practically, I find it makes it easier to calculate the value a compound sentence should take on a valuation. Think again about a valuation w such that w(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, and w(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}, and w(r) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, and suppose you want to know what w(p \land \neg (q \lor r)) is. (This is one of the examples we just looked at.) Now we can proceed as follows: since we know w(p), w(q), and w(r), we can dig into our compound sentence and replace those atomic sentences by the truth values they take on the valuation w. This gives us \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} \land \neg (\mathsf {\mathbf {F}} \lor \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}). And now we can proceed step-by-step just as before:
\mathsf {\mathbf {T}} \land \neg (\mathsf {\mathbf {F}} \lor \mathsf {\mathbf {T}})
\mathsf {\mathbf {T}} \land \neg \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}
\mathsf {\mathbf {T}} \land \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}
\mathsf {\mathbf {F}} This is just another way to arrive at the same answer, and we're doing the same things along the way. The difference is that going this way gives you a useful notation for writing down intermediate results. That can get really important; the more you try to hold in your head at once, the more likely you are to make a slip-up. By having a simple notation for intermediate results, you can make it much easier to make it through an entire calculation correctly.

